\begin_layout Standard
One way to solve this is to appeal to facts about the multivariate normal
 distribution that say that if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
y\\
\boldsymbol{x}
\end{array}\right)\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\left(\begin{array}{c}
\mu_{y}\\
\boldsymbol{\mu}_{x}
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\sigma_{y}^{2} & \Sigma_{y\boldsymbol{x}}\\
\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{x}y} & \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{xx}}
\end{array}\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 is potentially a vector of variables, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
x\\
z
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 in the context of this problem, then 
\begin_inset Formula $y|\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 has a normal distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[y|x\right]=\text{\ensuremath{\mu_{y}}}+\ensuremath{\Sigma}_{y\boldsymbol{x}}\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{xx}}^{-1}\left(\boldsymbol{x}-\boldsymbol{\mu}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and variance 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma^{2}-\Sigma_{y\boldsymbol{x}}\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{xx}}^{-1}\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{x}y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See for instance the Wikipedia page on the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "multivariate normal distribution"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_normal_distribution"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 From here, the problem is pretty mechanical.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the first part, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(y|x\right)=1+\frac{3}{5}\left(x-2\right)=-\frac{1}{5}+\frac{3}{5}x.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the second part, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(y|x,z\right)=1+\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 3\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
5 & 2\\
2 & 6
\end{array}\right)^{-1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
x-2\\
z-4
\end{array}\right)=1+\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{8}{13} & -\frac{1}{26}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
x-2\\
z-4
\end{array}\right)=\frac{1}{13}+\frac{8}{13}x-\frac{1}{26}z.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this solution is not very instructive â€“ it starts out with a fact
 about the normal distribution that mostly solves the problem for us.
 Furthermore, to derive the fact ourself (i.e., deriving the expressions for
 conditional distribution from the multivariate normal distribution) would
 be a pain and not necessarily illuminating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to proceed is to define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{i}\equiv y_{i}-E\left[y_{i}|x_{i}\right],
\]

\end_inset

and write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i}=E\left[y_{i}|x_{i}\right]+\varepsilon_{i}.\label{eq:regeq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, start with two facts that are less strong that the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $y|x$
\end_inset

 above: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $y|x$
\end_inset

 is normally distributed 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[y|x\right]$
\end_inset

 linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, the idea is to consider the properties of equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:regeq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and argue that we can apply our linear regression results to understand
 what its coefficients will be.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the second fact, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i}=\alpha+\beta x_{i}+\varepsilon_{i},\label{eq:regeq-linear}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[y|x\right]=\alpha+\beta x.
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 , we can use the law of iterated expectations to argue that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(\varepsilon_{i}|x_{i}\right)=E\left(y_{i}-E\left[y_{i}|x_{i}\right]|x_{i}\right)=E\left[y_{i}|x_{i}\right]-E\left[y_{i}|x_{i}\right]=0.
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, if we consider independently simulated data on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}|\boldsymbol{X}\right)=0$
\end_inset

, the strict exogeneity condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, notice that fact 1 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 is normally distributed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:regeq-linear"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) satisfies all the assumptions for the linear regression model with normally
 distributed error terms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the slides, we know that regressing 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (and a constant) with data simulated from the assumed distribution will
 yield the following coefficient estimates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\beta}=\frac{s_{xy}}{s_{x}^{2}}\qquad\qquad\widehat{\alpha}=\overline{y}-\widehat{\beta}\overline{x}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{xy}$
\end_inset

 refers to the sample covariance, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 refers to the sample variance, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}$
\end_inset

 refer to sample means.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's intuitive and easy to verify that the sample moments correspond to
 the population moments: 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[s_{xy}\right]=\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(s_{x}^{2}\right)=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Note: for the sample moments to be unbiased, we have to divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Bessel's correction"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bessel%27s_correction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Informally, this seems to suggest that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\widehat{\beta}\right]\approx\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

which would then imply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\widehat{\alpha}\right]\approx\mu_{y}-\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}}\mu_{x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If these results hold with equality, we can plug in the parameters from
 the population distribution, and we arrived at the same solution as above.
 (A similar argument can be applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[y|x,z\right]$
\end_inset

.) For large sample sizes, it's intuitive that the sample moments 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{xy}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 will be very close to their population analogs, so it makes sense that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\beta}$
\end_inset

 should be close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 for a large sample.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make this proof strategy formally complete, we need to argue that equality
 does hold
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\widehat{\beta}\right]=E\left[\frac{s_{xy}}{s_{x}^{2}}\right]=\frac{E\left[s_{xy}\right]}{E\left[s_{x}^{2}\right]}=\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

The non-obvious part is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\frac{s_{xy}}{s_{x}^{2}}\right]=\frac{E\left[s_{xy}\right]}{E\left[s_{x}^{2}\right]},
\]

\end_inset

which is true because 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{xy}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are independent, but it's not immediately obvious that they are independent
 because they both rely on the same data.
 The independence argument can be established by starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and extending the argument by induction, or it can be done more elegantly
 with a change in variables.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "this discussion"
target "https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/47350/proof-of-the-independence-of-the-sample-mean-and-sample-variance"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an example of the latter proof strategy.
 
\end_layout

